Rick Muller,

Some years ago I helped develop a kinetic reaction mechanism for 
tritium oxidation, which included electrons as one of the chemical 
species.  You can find the mechanism discussed in Failor et al., J. 
Phys. Chem. 96 (9): 3742-3752 (1992), and references 10 and 11 of 
that paper discuss the details of the mechanism itself.  The concept 
is that the energetic electrons from beta decay of tritium have 
enough energy to facilitate hydrogen oxidation, even in the absence 
of an elevated temperature to provide thermal energy.

Charlie Westbrook






